 This text file is an explanation of the command words, variables, and any
     other information related to the Lord scripting language, "Lady".

ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Quick Intro ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ
  Lady is a scripting language that allows anyone to write their own random
  events. The default random events can be found in EVENTS.LDY and can be
  edited.

- Each line is read, and unless told to, is not displayed.

- Want to make a comment somewhere in your quests? All text after a ; will
  be ignored.. There is an exception.. All text between a @display and
  @EndDisplay pair is displayed.

- Getting funny results from a script? Add /debug to your command line..
  lady.log wil be created with a step by step run down of what all Lady did.
  During beta testing, someone would tell me "such and such is saying:
  ERROR".. Id get their lady.log from them, and be able to tell exactly
  what the problem was.. Very useful if youre creating any scripts!

- Want to see your script in action? Add /debug to the command line,
  go into the forest and hit X.. This will look for the quest "TEST"
  in the file "test.ldy" .. You can edit that event and make it do
  whatever you want, including running your own events.

ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Events - Files ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ

Events, like IGMS, should each be distributed in their own files. This means
that if you create 3 different events, you should put each one in their
own file, and follow the EVENT formats that follow this section of the
documentation.

Also of note. There are a few reserved filenames. They are:

- LORD.LDY .. This holds the controling event for the random forest events.
- INN.LDY .. This holds the controlling event for leaving the Inn
- BANK.LDY .. This holds the controlling event for leaving the bank
- 3rdparty.dat .. This is obviously not a lady script file, however, events
  can be run from here. So therefore, dont mess with it.


ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Events - INSTALL ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ

@#INSTALL

Lets assume that Joe Smith writes his own event. It is in a file named
bigjoe.ldy .. He passes that file around to other sysops for them to run.
The other sysops will go into Lordcfg, into the Editors section, and choose
the Events editor. From there, the sysop would choose to (A)dd an event.
A new screen pops up with a blank event, but there is an option to (I)mport
event. The sysop chooses this, lordcfg prompts for the filename of the event.
The sysop puts in bigjoe.ldy .. Lordcfg will now look for and run the
event named @#INSTALL .. If that event does NOT exist, the event cannot
be imported! And if it cannot be imported, the sysop will have to manually
add in all the data needed for your event. Not good. So use this event!

Normal lady commands cannot be executed from the INSTALL event. Instead, only
the following commands can be used:

@eventname <string>

   Once Lordcfg has completed importing the event, it will recreate the
   right file. @eventname is the name of the actual event to run from
   your file. Not used for Forest, Leaving Bank, or Leaving Inn events,
   but _IS_ used (and thus required) for Other Places events.

@author <string>

   This is where you put your name or handle. This command is required.

@authid <string>

   This should be a unique string for your event and its version. For
   example, your create an event named @#BIGJOE and this is the first
   version of it, then @authid should be something like
   @authid BIGJOE1 .. This command is VERY required. And do make sure
   that you pick a unique string. It can be up to 255 characters long,
   Im sure you can pick something unique, eh? :)

@replace <string>

   Now lets assume that you've fixed some bugs in @#BIGJOE. You pass
   around a new file, bigjoe2.ldy .. You would use @replace to replace
   version one of your event. Lets assume that your @authid is now
   BIGJOE2 .. @replace BIGJOE1 would remove the BIGJOE1 event, and replace
   it with BIGJOE2. .. If you don't have to (or want to) replace an
   event, then you do not have to have this command.

@makedir <string>

   Lady scripts can create their own textfiles. Its a good idea to put
   these files in a subdirectory under Lord's directory (There's already
   a ton of files in the Lord dir, why add more to that collection?
   Please organize your files!) .. Of course, if you don't need this
   command, then you can leave it out.

@codebegin
@codeend

   When lordcfg recreates LORD.LDY, it will create a @case statement
   to handle all of the possible events. Everything between
   @codebegin and @codeend (up to 10 lines) will be put into LORD.LDY
   where your event is called.

   For most people, only one line is needed
   @runsub BIGJOE &filename

   But you can get fancy, if you wanted:
   @begin
      if &Pht > &Phx 1
        @runsub BIGJOE &filename
      @else 1
        @runsub LORD LORD.LDY
      @endif 1
   @end;

   Note 1:

   Something to take note of. Imagine that you create an event named
   @#BIGJOE and put it in a file named bigjoe.ldy .. You pass it around,
   and people install it. Okay. No problems there. But then someone else
   (Bob, who doesnt know about your event) creates their own bigjoe.ldy
   Now the sysop that already has yours installed, and is trying to install
   Bob's event, will run into a problem. Two different events, but the same
   filename. So, the sysop plays it safe and renames Bob's bigjoe.ldy to
   bigbob.ldy .. Okay, Lordcfg wont have a problem with that. But.. What if
   Bob referenced the actual filename "bigjoe.ldy" in his script? Bob's
   event would then have problems.

   Therefore. Use &filename in the code between @codebegin and @codeend
   Lordcfg will replate it with the actual filename being installed.

   Note 2:

   If you do get fancy, and need a "fallback" event, do a:
   @runsub LORD LORD.LDY
   when needed. This will just restart the random event picker.

@target <where>

   Use this to specify where your event will be ran from. Possible values
   are FOREST .. LEAVEINN .. LEAVEBANK .. OTHERPLACES

   If you leave this command out, your event will default to the forest.

@disp <some string>

   This is only required if you your target is OTHERPLACES .. More
   specifically, this will be the string displayed to the player.
   Let me restate something: This is _required_ if your target
   is OTHERPLACES.


ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Events - UNINSTALL ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ

The event @#UNINSTALL is called at 2 different times.

1) When the sysop chooses the Uninstall option in Lordcfg

2) When your version 2 replaces version 1.

Normal Lady commands cannot be run here. Instead only the following commands
work..

@del <filename or filemask opr &filename>

   If your event creates any files, its a good idea to remove them whenever
   your event is uninstalled.

   @del mydir/myfile.txt

   or

   @del mydir/*.*

   or to remove the actual event file

   @del &filename

   Note the use of &filename .. See The last section of "EVENTS - INSTALL"
   for the reasons to use this variable.

@rmdir <dirname>

   If you created and used a subdirectory for your event's files, make
   sure to remove the directory when uninstalling. Please note: _You_
   have to make sure the directory is empty before doing a @rmdir .. If
   the directory is not empty, then the @rmdir will fail.


ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Events - MAINT ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ

Do you need to have maintenance run on your event? No problem! Add an event
to your event file named @#MAINT and it will be ran when Lord runs its own
daily maintenance.

Any normal Lady command can be used here.



ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Variables ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ

These are case sensitive. Some, the numvars and player numvars, can be
used with other @commands. Most others, however, are only used with
@write and @writeln. See if you can come up with a new use for them!


&rnd<num> - will give you a random number between 1 and <num>..
            can be used for most everything.. make sure to drop the < >'s
            the <num> can be a number, a &P var or a &N var..
&S1..40   - displays 1 of 40 different string variables..
            e.g. &S15 for the 15th..  max length: 79  default: empty
&N1..40   - displays 1 of 40 different number variables..
            e.g. &N24 for the 24th..  max amount: 2,147,483,647 default: 0
&B1..40   - 40 different boolean (true/false) variables -  default: false

&P - As of this writing, there are 38 player variables.. See the
     "Player vars" section for a list, and a description of each.

&I1 &I2 and &I3 - File handles.. To be used with @openfile, @rewritefile,
        @appendfile, @closefile, and the @read's and @write's.

&lorddir  - the directory where lord is installed (read only)
&clean    - boolean.. Is the game in clean mode?  (read only)
&file_created - boolean .. for use with @openfile, @rewritefile
            and @appendfile (read only)
&F        - displays user's first name (read only)
&L        - displays user's last name (read only)
&name     - The user's first and last name (read only)
&nick     - users name in the game (read only)
&time     - the users time left in minutes (read only)
&ver      - will be replaced with the Lord's version number (read only)
&rip      - true is RIP is enabled
&hero     - the name of the last player to beat the dragon
&play     - the player's number from player.dat
&playedtoday - either 1 (true) or 0 (false).. whether the player has seen
            this event today or not

*note for the &S, &N, and &B var's.. if the specified number isnt between
1 and 40, then itll default to 1. As in, &S1003 will do &S1 and &N862
will do &N1 .. same for anything else that uses these variable sets.

When &N vars are displayed, they will have commas in them..

All number variables are of integer type.. Meaning, decimals not
allowed.

ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Screen Commands ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ

Here are a list of the various screen control commands.. These are only used
with @write, @writeln, and @display..

foreground color -
`1 dark blue     `6 brownish      `! light cyan     and seldom used
`2 dark green    `7 grey          `@ light red      `^ black
`3 dark cyan     `8 dark grey     `# light violet
`4 dark red      `9 light blue    `$ yellow
`5 dark violet   `0 light green   `% white

** Note.. The black foreground here is only available here. Lady authors
   are expected to use it wisely..

background color -
`r0 black               `r4 dark red
`r1 dark blue           `r5 dark violet
`r2 dark green          `r6 brownish
`r3 dark cyan           `r7 grey

Misc
`c - clears the screen, goes down 2 lines
`` - shows a `
@@ - shows a @
`l - displays the -=-=-=-=-=-=-=- line..
`k <text> - will center <text> on that line.. `k has to be the first 2 chars
   on that line..

ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ @Commands (AT Commands) ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ

While these arent case specific, they do have to be on their own line.
Be sure to check the file "events.ldy" for examples.

@#<questname> - signifies the beginning of the quest
@clrscr - clears the screen
@write <whatever> - writes whatever
@writeln <whatever> - writes whatever and adds a carriage return
@endquest - tells the quest engine its done with the file. should be
            the very last line.
@closequest - tells the quest engine its done with the quest. if the current
              quest is the last quest in the file, its not needed.
@display    - displays each line after it as the line is read (with color)
@enddisplay - stops the @display command.
@hitakey - waits for a keypress, even in @display mode.

@delay <number>

    This tells Lady to wait for <number> milliseconds. 100 is a second.
    If you dont specify the number, it will wait for 100 milliseconds.

@verreq <number>

    So youve written an event that works great with the current version
    of lord, but doesnt work with previous versions.. Use this to make
    sure that the sysop is running the proper version. <number>
    would be the lord version number, without periods, spaces, or anything.
    For example. @verreq 407

@endgame

    This will kick the player out of the game.

@choice - lemme see if i can explain this.. Itd be better if I gave you
          an example, and tore it down for you..

          @choice ABCD `2Whats your command? `8[`7A`8BCD]

          Alright.. First, youve got the @command.. "@choice"
          then youve got "ABCD" .. which are the acceptable keys the
          user can hit. If the user hits a key thats not in that bunch,
          the first letter will be used instead. The rest of the line is
          what the user will actually see. SANSI commands can be used there.

@case - @case response/responce/<numeric or boolean value> <case ID>

        This command is meant to handle @choice commands, and &N vars..
        Watch:

@choice ABCD `2Whats your command? `8[ABCD]

@case response 1
A: @begin
    @displayfile warrior.ans
    @hitakey
   @end
B: @displayfile mystic.ans
C: @begin
    @writeln
    @writeln `$Thats the right key!
    @writeln
   @end
D: @displayfile thief.ans
@endcase 1

   or you could do something like..

@set &N1 to &rnd10
@case &N1 7
1: @writeln its 1!
2: @writeln its 2!
3: @writeln its 3!
@endcase 7

   @case only works for response,numeric, or boolean values. "response"
   can be "response" or "responce".. either works.. Notice in the &N
   example that I didn't use all the numbers it could be. You dont have
   to.. You dont have to with "response" either.. but you DO have to
   have the @endcase and matching ID number!

   Whats the deal with the ID number? That allows you to have as many
   case statements nested within each other as you want.. example..

   case &N1 1
   12: @begin
        @case &N2 2
        23: @begin
             @case &N3 3
             @endcase 3
            @end
        @endcase 2
      @end
   @endcase 1

   The above example is perfectly legal.. doesnt do much of anything tho.
   No, the ID numbers do not have to be in sequential (1,2,3...) order..
   They couldve been 1, 98, and  1000002 .. Just so much as theyre all
   unique..


@prompts <which &S var to save to> <max length> <true or false>

   Used to get a string from the user. whatever the user types in will be
   stored in one of the &S variables. Use it like so:

   @prompt 3 60 true

   Youve got the @prompt command.. then which &S var to put it into, then
   the maximum length the user can go to.. If the last word is "true" then
   a blue background will show up.. if the last is "false" or left off, the
   blue background wont show up. Color codes are allowed, but dangerous ones
   are striped off..

@promptn <which &N var to save to> <max length of allowed numbers>

   @promptn 21 2

   Prompt for a number.. Store it in the 21st &N variable, and the number
   entered will have a max length of 2 numbers. 99 = length of 2..
   1234567890 = length of 10..

@math <where the result should go> = <number> <+,-,*,/,!> <number>
   If the result would go negative, then its ignored. "Divide by zero" is
   also ignored.. The result has to go to a &N variable. You can use
   &N vars, &P vars, and numbers to get that result..

   examples:

   @math &N1 = &N2 + &N3  ; addition
   @math &N1 = &N2 - 50   ; subtraction
   @math &N1 = 100 * &N3  ; multiplication
   @math &N1 = &N2 / 2    ; divide, throw away remainder
   @math &N1 = &N2 ! &N3  ; divide, only keep the remainder

   *note: 15 / 2 equals 7.. 15 ! 2 equals 1

@displayfile <name> <filename>
   This is used to display an ansi or sansi file. If filename is left off,
   then itll display the entire file. Otherwise, itd be treated as a
   SANSI style database.. Where you have a bunch of screens in one file,
   and each has an @#<screentitle>.. You dont have to add the @# .. The
   engine will do it for you..

@label <labelname>
@goto <labelname>
   Using these 2 commands, you can make a script return to a specific
   place. the labels arent case specific... and yes, they can be used
   within @case's..

@if <operand 1> <comparison operator> <operand 2> <ID>
@begin
<block of code>
@end
@else <ID>
@begin
<block of code>
@end
@endif <ID>


   Using @if, you can check the value of a &variable. If the comparison
   is true, the first block of code is ran. If the comparison isn't true,
   and there is a second block of code, the second block will be ran.

   Comparison operators are, and the type of comparison:
     is,=     : equal
     <>,!=    : not equal
     <        : less than
     >        : greater than

   &B, &P, &N, &S, &clean, &file_created are all acceptable operands.
   If the first operand is not preceded by an &, it be treated as a number.

   It is important to note that boolean values interpret to 1 for
   true, or 0 for false. This also means that you could compare a
   boolean to a number. For example: @if &B1 = &N1 ..
   When comparing booleans, operand 2 could be 1, T, or true,
   or 0, F, or false.

   String variables can only be compared against string variables,
   or one word strings. If you want to have a multiple word operand,
   put it in a string variable. Lady will determine if you are doing
   a string comparison based on the first operand.

   When comparing strings, keep in mind that it is case sensitive.
   'LORD' is not the same as 'lord'.

   <ID> doesn't have to be a number, a letter.. They just have to match.

   You do not have to have an @else, but you do have to have an @endif.

   If <block of code> is only one line, you do not have to have the
   @begin/@end pair.

   Examples:

   @if &B7 is true 1        @if &Psx is false sexcheck
     @begin                      @writeln The player is female!
       stuff                    @else sexcheck
       stuff                     @begin
     @end                          @display
     @else 1                          You take Violet by the hand...
     @begin                                  but she rejects you!
       stuff                       @enddisplay
       stuff                     @end
     @end                      @endif sexcheck
   @endif 1


   * note .. You can have as many nested if/thens as you want..
    Whats a nested if/then?

   Example
    @if &N2 = &Pwn A
     @begin
      @if &N2 != &N3 true B
      ...
      @endif B
     @end
    @endif A

@upstr <&S var>
   Will make the &S variable all upper case..

@lowstr <&S var>
   Will make the &S variable all lowercase..

@set &B<num> to <true/false or t/f or 1/0>
@set &B<num> to !<true/1 or false/0>
@set &N<num> to +<a value>
@set &N<num> to -<a value>
@set &N<num> to <a value>
@set &S<num> to <whatever you like>

@set &P<which one> to <value>
@set &P<which one> to +<value>
@set &P<which one> to -<value>

   @set allows you to change the value of a &variable.

   If the variable that you are setting is a boolean and the value
   is preceded by an exclamation point, you will set the opposite of
   the value. In pascal, the equivalent would be &B := not <the value>

   If you are setting a &N or &P variable, and the value is preceded by a
   plus sign, you will increment the &variable with <the value>.

   If you are setting a &N or &P variable, and the value is preceded by a
   minus sign, you will decrement the &variable with <the value>.

   If you are setting a &P variable, the value has to be within range.
   If the value is not within range, the command will be ignored.

@runsub <which one> <which file>

   Need to chop your script into several different pieces? @RUNSUB will
   let you do that.. <which one> is the quest to run, and <which file>
   is the file the quest is in. You don't have to have a <which file>..
   If you omit it, then the current file is assumed. <which one> does
   not have to be in all capital letters.

   A @RUNSUB command will end whatever quest its called from.

   If you omit both the quest and the file, the LORD event will be ran from
   the LORD.LDY file.

   &variable values are inherited from the calling event. Meaning..
   Event one sets &N1 to 100, and then @runsub's event 2. &N1 will
   be equal to 100 in event 2. The only exception to this rule are the
   &I variables. Files are closed before a sub-event is ran.


@openfile &I<1,2,3> <filename>

   Opens a file and sets the file's pointer to the beginning of the file.
   If the file doesn;t exist, it will be created. You can have 3 different
   files open at any one time. If the file variable is already assigned
   to another file, you can't reassign it until your close it. @openfile
   will not open an .exe, .ovr, .dll, .bat, .com, or .sh files.

   If the file was created, the variable &file_created will be true.

   The <filename> you specify will have the lord's directory pre-prended
   onto it. This ensures that whatever files that Lady scripts create are
   in the Lord directory or a subdirectory.

   <filename> can contain a subdirectory. However, Lady will not create
   the subdir for you. You have to do that yourself.

   Note.. A system is limited in how many files it can have open at one
   time. This number is usually signified in config.sys by the line
   "FILES=10" or whatever. Obviously, the more files you have open,
   the closer you'll get to the system's limit. This isn't something to
   be overly concerned about, but it is something to keep in mind if
   you use all 3 file variables at one time. Think about it.. You have
   3 files open at once, on 10 nodes.. That'd be 30 open files.. Plus
   the files that Lord has open.. Plus any files that any other programs
   have open.. Again.. Not something to be overly concerned about..
   Just something to keep in mind.

@rewritefile &I<1,2,3> <filename>

   Recreates the specified file. That is.. if <filename> exists when you
   do a @rewritefile, it will be overwritten as a zero byte / empty file.

   &file_created will always be true upon success.

   As with @openfile, lord's directory will be pre-pended onto the front
   of the filename.

   As with @openfile, <filename> can contain a subdir. But you have to
   create the directory yourself.

@appendfile &I<1,2,3> <filename>

   Opens a file and sets the file pointer to the end of the file. If the
   file does not exist, it will be created.

   If the file is created, the variable &file_created will be true

   <filename> can contain subdirectories, but Lady will not create the
   subdir for you. You have to do that yourself.

   Lord's directory will be prepended onto the beginning of the filename.

@closefile &I<1,2,3>

   Closes a file that was previously open by @openfile. Lady will clean
   up after you by closing any files you left open, but you should still
   close the file yourself. Its good scripting mojo.

@writeln &I<1,2,3> <anything>

   After doing an @openfile, you can use @writeln to write to the file.

@readline &I<1,2,3> &S1-40
@readline &I<1,2,3> &N1-40

   After doing an @openfile, you can use @readline to read either a
   string or a number


@saveplayer

   This forces Lord to save the player's data.

@changearm <1..15>
@changewep <1..15>

   These commands change the player's armour or weapon.

@setbit &N1-40 1-32 on|off
@setbit &N1-40 1-32 true|false
@setbit &N1-40 1-32 1|0

   Sometimes you need more boolean variables than the 40 thats
   alloted by lady. Using a &N variable, you can use an additional
   32 booleans for each &N thats used in a bitwise manner.

   An example:

   @set &N1 to 0 ; always zero it out first
   @setbit &N1 1 true

@isbitset &N1-40 1-32 &N1-40
@isbitset <var to check> <bit to check> <var to save the result in>

   Returns either a 1 (true) or 0 (false)

   An Example:

   @set &N1 to 0
   @setbit &N1 1 true
   @isbitset &N1 1 &N2
   @if &N2 = 1 then 1
     @writeln The bit is set!
   @endif 1


@DEBUG ON
@DEBUG OFF
@DEBUG SUPER ON
@DEBUG SUPER OFF

These commands toggle the logging done by Lady.

Normal debug ("DEBUG ON" to turn it on, and "DEBUG OFF" to turn it off)
only logs your normal things. This is the equivalent of adding /DEBUG to
the command line.

Super debug ("@DEBUG SUPER ON" and "@DEBUG SUPER OFF") turn on _major_
logging. A lot more will be logged with this, however, this can create
_Very_ large log files very quickly.

Note: If your script does a @DEBUG ON or a @DEBUG SUPER ON, but does not
turn it off, logging _Stays_ on until the program is exited.



ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Player Stats ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ
Want to modify the player's stats? Use the mail codes! The same mail codes
that can be used by IGMs can be used in Lady! They have to be at the
beginning of the line.. Check a Lady file, or a mailxx.dat for examples..
Of course, you could use @set .. ;>

`b<amount> this deposites the amount in the readers bank account.
`G<amount> this puts the amount in the readers 'money in hand'.
`E<amount> this adds to the readers experience by amount.
`$<account num>  Makes user MARRIED to this person. (-1 for not married)
`{ this increments the 'number of lays' stat of the reader.
`} {this increments the readers charm.)
`+<amount>  Users charm BECOMES this number. (Used in divorce mail-backs)
`K this increments the amount of kids the reader has.
`M<amount>  This increments readers Strength
`D<amount>  This increments readers Defence
`,<amount>  This increments forest fights per that day
`:<amount>  This increments user fighters per that day
`;<amount>  This increments readers Hitpoint Max

   (Note, the above mail codes can decrement if a - is placed before num.
   Checking is done to make sure user does not go below certain levels)

`S This raises the readers SKILL in his current class.  Will not let the
   skill pass 40.

How to use these mail codes? Use them with a @write @writeln or @display
command.. they have to be the only thing on the line, and they have to be
at the beginning of the line. examples..

@writeln `0Youve just defeated the Red Dragon!
@write `E10000

@display
  `0Youve just defeated the Red Dragon!
`E10000
@enddisplay

ﾉﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｻ
ｺ ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ Player Variables ｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰｰ ｺ
ﾈﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍｼ
These are the player variables. They can be used most everywhere. Screen
commands will display the value instead of the variables, where ever you
could put a number, etc. If you try to set a variable outside of its range,
it'll be ignored. In other words,

@set &Pba to 2000000000

would be fine, while

@set &Pba to 5000000000

would be ignored.

numbers
-------
&Pan {armor num ..                                 Range: 1 to 15}
&Pba {gold in bank ..                              Range: 0 to 2 billion}
&Pch {charm ..                                     Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Pcl {player's class.. 1 (warrior), 2 (mystic man), or 3 (thief)}
&Pde {total def points ..                          Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Pex {xp points ..                                 Range: 0 to 2 billion}
&Pff {forest fights ..                             Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Pgo {gold in hand ..                              Range: 0 to 2 billion}
&Pge {# of gems on hand ..                         Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Phf {human fights ..                              Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Pht {current hit points ..                        Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Phx {max hp ..                                    Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Pki {# of kids ..                                 Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Pkd {# of times player has killed the dragon ..   Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Ply {player lays stat ..                          Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Plv {hmmmm ..                                     Range: 1 to 12}
&Plw {number of Death Knight uses left today ..    range: 0 to 100}
&Plm {number of Mystical skill uses left today ..  range: 0 to 100}
&Plt {number of Thieving skill uses left today ..  range: 0 to 100}
&Ppk {# of player kills ..                         Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Psr {total str points ..                          Range: 0.. 32,000}
&Psw {number of Death Knight skill points ..       range: 0 to 100}
&Psm {number of Mystical skill points ..           range: 0 to 100}
&Pst {number of Thieving skill points ..           range: 0 to 100}
&Pwn {wep num ..                                   range: 1 to 15}

booleans (true or false)
--------
&Pam     {does player carry amulet of accuracy? 1=true, 0 = false}
&Pdd     {true=dead}
&Pdi     {did player divorce today?}
&Pdr     {seen dragon today?}
&Pse     {seen master today?}
&Psx     {true=female}
&Psb     {seen bard?}
&Pho     {has a horse?}
&Phi     {high spirits?}
&Pfa     {true=player has a fairy}
&Pfl     {if true, player has flirted that day}
&Pfi     {flirted in inn?}
&Pma     {is player married? cant set this.}

strings (none of these can be set.)
-------
&Pmn     {name of person married to, cant set this..}
&Pwe     {wep name}
&Par     {armor name}

numbers {that cant be changed}
-------
&Ppl     {player's record position in player.dat}
